    <!-- Translation notes -->
    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>All examples use finite lists of finite distributions as credal sets. The paper works with convex sets of probability measures over measurable spaces, the Para construction on arbitrary Markov categories, and graded monads indexed by a quantale of imprecision levels.</p>
    <p>For example: this page's lower/upper expectation iterates over three coin distributions. In the paper, the same construction applies to credal sets of Gaussian measures over ℝⁿ, where the lower expectation becomes an optimization problem over an infinite-dimensional convex set. The bracket structure (min/max over the set) is identical. The measure theory and optimization are not.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 text-center text-sm text-gray-400 mt-10">
      Ready for the real thing? <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.09391"><img src="/reading/arxiv.webp" alt="arxiv" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/> Read the paper</a>. Start at §3 for the Para construction, §5 for graded monads and Markov categories.
    </div>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-6">Framework connection: Imprecise probability via the Para construction generalizes the Natural Framework's ambient category from precise to credal-set-valued stages. (<a href="https://june.kim/ambient-category"><img src="/reading/jk.png" alt="jk" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Ambient Category</a>)</p>

